Not once  did our hostess come over to apologize or to maybe just make small conversations. Instead she sat with another employee and whispered back and forth.  Once our food came it wasn't like  the usual. Grits were loose my fiance fish was over cooked  me and my sons meal was missing the bacon bits that usually comes with the shrimp and grits  our Orange juice was warm and tasted like they used old oranges. This experience really shocked me.  My fiance was also asked for his id. After the order was placed for a belini. In which we were never asked for in the past.  We are in our late 40's. Then we were charged for unlimited belinis. We asked for mimosas, however they didn't have none.  It was just a whole Vibe. But definitely not a pleasant one. I don't think we will ever return. Live jazz and karaoke and awesome fried fish/chicken/shrimp specials on Fridays. . .what more could you ask for in a cozy local spot. Went out with the hubby for date night in the neighborhood and walked in on live music and singing. We both opted for the fried chicken special, which came with two sides. We both chose greens and macaroni & cheese. I had no idea there was feta in the mac & cheese and my pregnant, sensitive nose couldn't stand the spoiled milk smell. After talking to Donna, the owner, she politely explained there was feta in the dish and offered a substitute. I got the baked sweet potatoes and was satisfied. The chicken was moist, crispy, and flavorful. The cornbread was a bit dry for my taste, but good, nonetheless. The greens were as good as my mother's, with a nice smoky taste and not too salty. I enjoyed a blended melon and mint drink, which would have been great, if it wasn't for all of the melon chunks and half-ground seeds. I couldn't enjoy it through my straw. It also tasted as if the melons weren't ripe enough, as the drink is not sweet. Hubby had one with pineapple, ginger and mint, which was much more flavorful, but almost as chunky as mine. For dessert, we ordered a couple of slices of sweet potato pie to-go. The pie is always good. You'll just have to try it to see what I mean. The best part of our experience was the genuinely warm atmosphere. Not only were Donna and her staff cordial, but even the live entertainment was friendly and engaging. The singer even dedicated a few songs to our baby-to-be. We really enjoy this hidden gem and plan on patronizing more often!

My frittata came with copious amounts of food (for only $12) however the frittata itself was salty and again underwhelming. While I might have missed the sign, I was not alerted that they were cash only until after I ordered which meant I had to find an ATM before I could pay for my food.

The service was miserable. Took forever, no refills on coffee or water, brought out the wrong drinks, plates had their sides mixed up. The food was good, but certainly not great. Turkey sausage and Turkey bacon are the only options, somewhat annoying.
Nice place

The food was good. I tried their farmer's breakfast (sorry if the name is not right!) and it was filling and delicious. Service on my few visits has been inconsistent, with one time the place being empty but the service being very slow.
Food is cool

Horrible service. Very overpriced, $12 for a croissant and two eggs, $20 for an omelet.  Service was incredibly slow, took about an hour to get a croissant and two eggs.  I asked the waitress why this was taking so long and instead of listening and responding politely, she raised her voice and started talking over me. Very rude, especially when you are being made to wait like that.  Then, when it was time to pay the bill they told me the credit card machine wasn't working and I needed to go to the ATM. Honestly a horrible experience.  At least the eggs weren't half bad.

Absolutely love the place. No, it is not "fast food," but who wants that? When I go out with friends, I enjoy their company enough to take time. The wait is totally worth it and I prefer food that is freshly prepared with attention and dedication. This is also one of the places with the most welcoming atmosphere here in Harlem, where so many just seem to want to make a quick buck off the changing demographic. Very homey indeed, with interesting, varied furniture and changing art exhibits. And friendly service!

With a senior with two knee replacements, it was obvious that stepping up to get in this place indicated that they did not welcome any disability. Once we entered, we were not allowed to sit in the booth (we were told it was reserved for a party of five), although no party ever came for those seats. Our waitress could not answer basic questions, and made no attempt to find out. Once we ordered, we were served beverages. As we waited, a party of four (we were three) entered; their orders were taken and they were served promptly, while we still waited. Finally, we were asked what else we were drinking, so we ordered Mimosas & orange juice. These were served, meanwhile we simply waited for our food while those who came after us were enjoying their meals. No matter what we ordered, we should have been served well before the larger party entered. Needless to say, we opted to leave cash for our drinks on the table and leave. Could it be that they prefer City College students and faculty, even on Sunday? We ended up at Cafe Latte on Lenox before driving to Philadelphia. No, we will never return. Other reviewers seems to enjoy the food; unfortunately, we never got that far.

Unacceptable service. After we ordered, we waited around 1 hour and still had no food or message from the waitress. Only 1 or 2 other tables of people but we didn't get a refill on anything. We were told several times the order was coming out and it did not. Finally, the food came out and my vegetarian girlfriend's meal had sausage after requesting no meat. We left immediately after. Cool spot, would like to try again but unacceptable this time.

They have a very homely atmosphere with brick walls and low lighting. The space is great for groups. The service was wonderful and attentive. We ordered the St. Nicholas Park Turkey burger and the Riverside park burger, which was a salmon burger, and cheese and noodle souffle. We went around 7pm on a Tuesday and the place was pretty empty.  Check out this place if you want good, organic food! Or even just good food!
Delicious breakfast croissant sandwhch. Hit the spot.

The first time I went to HSH, I honestly was not very impressed. I had turkey bacon, grits, toast, eggs, and orange juice.  I am glad that I gave it a second try, because their fish and grits meal was AMAZING! The fish was fried and had a side of eggs and grits with butter (you can have cheese with your grits too if that's your thing).  The only meals I have had at the restaurant were breakfast, but I would be interested in returning and checking out their lunch/dinner options.

Nice little haven in Harlem. Decor was cool, and the place is clean. The rest was not impressive though. Service was pretty terrible - took forever to get our order taken, coffee, then milk for coffee, and food. Once we finally got it, the food was okay. Would give them another try sometime, but in no hurry.

I been planning on this visiting this location for months.  Today I ended up on this side of Harlem today and said what day is better than the PRESENT! I went around brunch time on a Friday.  I consider myself a French Toast connisueer.  The organic  challah french toast with organic maple syrup was amazing. Great flavor and cooked perfectly.  The menu they had was very diverse which definitely makes me want to make another visit VERY SOON. Everything from sandwiches to soups to salads to delicious entrées.  The staff and service was very personable and that is something I value just as much as great food.  The staff made me feel at home . Guess that's why it is called Home Sweet Harlem.  Met the owner and she is as sweet as pie and truly has a passion for food & her business.  PLEASE DON'T LET THE NEGATIVE REVIEWS KEEP YOU FROM STOPPING INTO THIS HARLEM GEM!! I Plan on becoming a regular there.  Hope the staff doesn't get tired of seeing my face :)

The atmosphere at this eatery is definitely homey. The staff is friendly but spread a little thin. The selection provided by the menu is sparse at best, this restaurant still has a lot of development to do.
Awesome fish tacos and a unique circular booth in the corner.
